    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-31T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-31T02:00:00-05:00" n="660"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d660">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/473: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-31T16:00:00+09:00"
                            >January 31, 1938—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 31—6:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>59. Department’s 31, January 30, 1 p.m., integrity of Chinese customs. My British
                    colleague received his instructions today and is prepared <pb facs="0644"
                        n="640" xml:id="pg_640"/> to act. I have therefore today presented to the
                    Japanese Government a note conforming precisely to the Department’s text.<note
                        n="43" xml:id="d660fn43">See <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_738">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 738</ref>; the Department on January 31
                        also replied to the British Embassy’s inquiry on this subject. For reply of
                        the Japanese Foreign Office, on March 22, see <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v01#pg_742">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 742</ref>; it replied likewise to
                        British and French representations.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai for repetition to Hankow and Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
